  "prompt": "Which day can be the first and the last day of a century?",
  "response": "A century is a period of 100 years.\nLet's consider the Gregorian calendar.\nThe Gregorian calendar repeats every 400 years, and in this 400-year period, there are 100 leap years, minus 3 leap years divisible by 100, plus 1 leap year divisible by 400. So there are $100 - 3 + 1 = 97$ leap years.\nSo there are $400 \\times 365 + 97 = 146000 + 97 = 146097$ days in a 400-year cycle.\nSince $146097 \\equiv 146097 \\pmod 7$, we have $146097 = 20871 \\times 7$, so $146097 \\equiv 0 \\pmod 7$. Thus, a 400-year cycle ends on the same day of the week that it starts on.\n\nThe length of a non-leap year is 365 days. Since $365 \\equiv 1 \\pmod 7$, each regular year shifts the day of the week forward by one.\nThe length of a leap year is 366 days. Since $366 \\equiv 2 \\pmod 7$, each leap year shifts the day of the week forward by two.\nA century is 100 years. In 100 years, there are 24 or 25 leap years.\nLet's say there are 24 leap years. Then the number of days in a century is $100 \\times 365 + 24 = 36500 + 24 = 36524$ days.\n$36524 \\pmod 7 = (36500 + 24) \\pmod 7 = (365 \\times 100 + 24) \\pmod 7 = (1 \\times 100 + 24) \\pmod 7 = 124 \\pmod 7 = (124 - 70 - 49) \\pmod 7 = 5 \\pmod 7$.\nSo in a century with 24 leap years, the last day of the century is 5 days after the first day of the century.\nIf there are 25 leap years, then the number of days in a century is $100 \\times 365 + 25 = 36500 + 25 = 36525$ days.\n$36525 \\pmod 7 = (36500 + 25) \\pmod 7 = (365 \\times 100 + 25) \\pmod 7 = (1 \\times 100 + 25) \\pmod 7 = 125 \\pmod 7 = (125 - 70 - 49) \\pmod 7 = 6 \\pmod 7$.\nSo in a century with 25 leap years, the last day of the century is 6 days after the first day of the century.\n\nThe possible days of the week for the last day of the century, if the first day is Monday, are Saturday (5 days later) and Sunday (6 days later).\nLet's assume the first day of the century is day 0 (Monday), then the last day is either $0 + 5 = 5$ (Saturday) or $0 + 6 = 6$ (Sunday).\nThen the last day of the century can be Monday + 5 = Saturday or Monday + 6 = Sunday.\nIf the first day is Tuesday, the last day can be Sunday or Monday.\nIf the first day is Wednesday, the last day can be Monday or Tuesday.\nIf the first day is Thursday, the last day can be Tuesday or Wednesday.\nIf the first day is Friday, the last day can be Wednesday or Thursday.\nIf the first day is Saturday, the last day can be Thursday or Friday.\nIf the first day is Sunday, the last day can be Friday or Saturday.\n\nThe days of the week are Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday.\nWe know that the century starts with the year divisible by 100. So years 100, 200, 300, 400, 500, 600, etc., are divisible by 100.\nThe possible days for the last day of the century are Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday.\nThe last day of the century can be any of these days.\nThe first day of the century can be any of these days.\n\nIn the Gregorian calendar, a century can start on any day of the week.\nThe last days of the centuries are 100, 200, 300, 400, ...\nThe day on which the last day of a century falls can be Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday.\nHowever, it is impossible for a century to end on a Sunday, Wednesday or Friday.\nTherefore, the last day of a century can be Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday.\n\nHowever, the first day of a century can be any day of the week.\n\nPossible pairs of (first day, last day) are (Monday, Saturday), (Monday, Sunday), (Tuesday, Sunday), (Tuesday, Monday), (Wednesday, Monday), (Wednesday, Tuesday), (Thursday, Tuesday), (Thursday, Wednesday), (Friday, Wednesday), (Friday, Thursday), (Saturday, Thursday), (Saturday, Friday), (Sunday, Friday), (Sunday, Saturday).\nWe need to determine which days can be the first and last days of a century.\nWe know the last day can only be Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, or Saturday.\nIf the last day is Monday, then the first day can be Tuesday or Wednesday.\nIf the last day is Tuesday, then the first day can be Wednesday or Thursday.\nIf the last day is Thursday, then the first day can be Saturday or Friday.\nIf the last day is Saturday, then the first day can be Monday or Sunday.\nThe possible first days are Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday.\nThe first day of the week can be any day. The last day of the week can be Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday.\n\nThe possible last days are Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday.\nThe possible first days are any day of the week.\nIf the last day is Monday, then the first day is Tuesday or Wednesday.\nIf the last day is Tuesday, then the first day is Wednesday or Thursday.\nIf the last day is Thursday, then the first day is Friday or Saturday.\nIf the last day is Saturday, then the first day is Sunday or Monday.\n\nHowever, the question asks which day can be both the first and last day of a century.\nIn the sequence: 0 1 2 3 4 5 6\nWe know that the possible last days are 1, 2, 4, 6.\nThe difference between the first and last days is 5 or 6.\nFor 1: -4 or -5. 1-4=-3 = 4, 1-5=-4 = 3. 1 can be the first day.\nFor 2: -3 or -4. 2-3 = -1 = 6, 2-4=-2 = 5. 2 can be the first day.\nFor 4: -1 or -2. 4-1 = 3, 4-2 = 2. 4 can be the first day.\nFor 6: +1 or 0. 6+1=0, 6-1=-2=-1. 6 could be the first day.\nThus, the first day can be 1, 2, 4, 6 = Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday.\n\nTherefore, Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, and Saturday are the only days that can be both the first and last day of a century.\n\nFinal Answer: The final answer is $\\boxed{Thursday}$",
